PROJECT SUMMARY 32-bit Floating-Point ALU:-

This project presents the design and implementation of a 32-bit floating-point Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) capable of 
performing both basic and advanced mathematical operations, it is a A hardware-based scientific calculator implemented using
RTL and Vivado. The ALU is designed using a modular approach, where each operation is implemented as an independent functional unit, improving scalability, clarity,
and ease of debugging. Based on the control signal, the ALU selects and outputs the result of the desired operation.

OBJECTIVE OF THE PROJECT
The motivation behind this project is to move beyond theoretical learning and work towards designing a real hardware system
with the long-term goal of building a chip. Through this project, I aimed to strengthen my understanding of Hardware
Description Languages (HDL) and RTL design by implementing a complete and functional ALU. Instead of limiting the design
to basic integer operations, I focused on developing a more practical system capable of handling complex computations. 
This approach helped me gain hands-on experience in digital design, modular architecture, and hardware-level problem 
solving. Ultimately, this project serves as a foundation for future work in VLSI design and chip implementation.


Floating-Point Representation:
All computations are performed using the IEEE 754 floating point standard, which represents numbers using three 
components: sign, exponent, and mantissa. Each module internally handles these components by decomposing the inputs,
performing the required operation, normalizing the result, and recombining them into a valid floating-point output. 
This ensures consistency, precision, and support for a wide range of values.


BASIC ARITHMETIC MODULES:
The ALU includes four primary arithmetic units

Floating-Point Adder (fp_adder)-
This module performs addition by first aligning the exponents of the two inputs. The mantissas are then added, followed by 
normalization and rounding to maintain proper format.

Floating-Point Subtractor (fp_subtractor)-
Similar to the adder, but performs subtraction of mantissas after exponent alignment. It also includes normalization to
ensure the result remains in proper floating-point form.

Floating-Point Multiplier (fp_multiplier)-
In this module, mantissas are multiplied while exponents are added (with bias adjustment). The result is then normalized 
and rounded to fit within the 32-bit format.

Floating-Point Divider (fp_divider)-
This unit divides mantissas and subtracts exponents accordingly. Post-division, normalization and rounding are applied to
produce the final result.



ADVANCED COMPUTATIONAL MODULES
To extend functionality beyond basic arithmetic, the ALU includes the following:

Square Root Module (fp_sqrt)
This module computes the square root of a floating-point number using the Newton-Raphson iterative method. Starting with an
initial approximation, the method refines the result through repeated iterations until sufficient accuracy is achieved. 
This approach is efficient and suitable for hardware implementation.

Quadratic Equation Solver (fp_quadratic)
This module computes the roots of a quadratic equation of the form ax² + bx + c = 0. It first calculates the discriminant
(b² − 4ac), then uses the square root module to evaluate it, and finally computes both roots using floating-point arithmetic.
The outputs are two values, x₁ and x₂, representing the solutions.


Control and Selection Logic

All module outputs are computed in parallel, and the final result is selected using a combinational case statement based on 
the 3-bit operation code:

000 → Addition
001 → Subtraction
010 → Multiplication
011 → Division
100 → Square Root
101 → First root of quadratic (x₁)
110 → Second root of quadratic (x₂)

This structure ensures fast operation selection and efficient data flow.


INTERCONNECTION AND DATA FLOW:

The ALU is designed such that all input values are simultaneously fed into the respective modules. Each module independently
computes its result, and the outputs are connected to a shared selection block. This parallel architecture reduces latency, 
as the ALU does not need to wait for one operation to finish before starting another.
The modular design also allows individual components to be tested and verified separately before integration, improving 
reliability and maintainability.


FUTURE SCOPE FOR THE ALU:

In terms of future scope, this project can be extended by adding more advanced mathematical operations such as statistical 
functions, permutations and combinations, and trigonometric computations. This would further enhance the capability of the 
ALU and make it suitable for more complex applications.
Additionally, the design can be taken beyond simulation by converting the RTL design into a physical ASIC layout using tools
like OpenLane, generating a GDS2 file. This would allow the ALU to be implemented as an actual hardware chip.
So, the project has strong potential to evolve from a functional design into a complete hardware implementation.








